randoop.types

Class ConcreteSimpleType

  • java.lang.Object
    • randoop.types.GeneralType
      • randoop.types.ConcreteType
        • randoop.types.ConcreteSimpleType

  • public class ConcreteSimpleType
extends ConcreteType
    ConcreteSimpleType represents an atomic concrete type: a primitive type, a non-generic class, an enum, or the rawtype for a generic class. It is a wrapper for a Class object, which is a runtime representation of a type.

      • isAssignableFrom

        public boolean isAssignableFrom(ConcreteType sourceType)
        Indicates whether a value of a ConcreteType can be assigned to a variable of this type: Variablethis = Expressionsourcetype. In other words, this is a legal assignment. Based on the definition of assignment context in section 5.2 of the JDK 8 Java Language Specification a value of one type is assignable to a variable of another type if the first type can be converted to the second by
        • an identity conversion,
        • a widening primitive conversion,
        • a widening reference conversion,
        • a boxing conversion, and
        • an unboxing conversion possibly followed by a widening conversion.
        And, if after all those conversions, the type is a raw type, an unchecked conversion may occur.

        When implementing this method, be aware that the method Class.isAssignableFrom(Class) checks identity and reference conversions, and does a comparison of raw types for parameterized types. The method PrimitiveTypes.isAssignable(Class, Class) checks identity and primitive widening for primitive types. Tests for assignability to this ConcreteSimpleType. Does not consider void assignable from/to any type.

        Overrides:
        isAssignableFrom in class ConcreteType
        Parameters:
        sourceType - the source type
        Returns:
        true if the source type can be assigned to this type by an assignment conversion, false otherwise
